    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.5.13" />
                
                <fw type="curatorial">13</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">THE MACMILLAN COMPANY
                        <lb/>
                    PUBLISHERS
                        <lb/>
                    64-66 FIFTH AVENUE
                        <lb/>
                    NEW YORK</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">BOSTON
                        <lb/>
                    CHICAGO
                        <lb/>
                    ATLANTA
                        <lb/>
                    DALLAS
                        <lb/>
                    SAN FRANCISCO</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">LONDON
                        <lb/>
                    TORONTO
                        <lb/>
                    BOMBAY
                        <lb/>
                    CALCUTTA
                        <lb/>
                    MELBOURNE</hi>
                </fw>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>March 19, 1918.</dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Bancroft, Nebr.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:&#8212;</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am wondering if I cannot get you to help me on some publicity for Hamlin Garland's <hi rend="caps">A SON OF THE MIDDLE BORDER</hi>. This may seem like a very presuming thing for me to suggest, but I am counting on your good nature and remembering your interest in Mr. Garland's story. I have made the suggestion to several papers that they re-print extracts from <hi rend="caps">A SON OF THE MIDDLE BORDER</hi>, giving full credit of course to the book. There are a great many sections of the book which are complete in themselves &#8212; 2000 words or so in length and which lend themselves nicely to reprinting in this fashion. A number of editors have taken up with the idea, and I would like to get others to do so, particularly in Minnesota, St. Paul, on the coast, and in the Middle West. Do you know of any editors whom I might approach? I would indeed welcome your advice as to the whole thing and any suggestions that you might care to make.</p>
                
                <p>I know you are an extremely busy man, and I do hope you will pardon my approaching you in this way.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours very truly</salute>
                
                    <signed>THE MACMILLAN COMPANY.
                    Editorial Department.</signed>
                    <signed><unclear reason="missing"/></signed>
                
                    <note>ESL/NS</note>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
